-- 28_parallel_enum_coloring — six independent dense 3-coloring
-- problems in one claim, each using enum-typed variables, looped
-- over 20 ticks so per-tick parallel savings amortize the one-shot
-- enum-context-replay setup cost.
--
-- Six independent searches over `enum Color`:
--   * No variable is shared across the six sub-problems → the body
--     decomposes into 6 independent components (visible as
--     `comp=…/8` in EVIDENT_FUNCTIONIZE_STATS=1).
--   * Each component is a 24-node 3-coloring with 24-cycle + skip-3
--     + skip-5 + skip-7 chord edges (~96 edges).
--   * The FSM loops 20 ticks (`tick ∈ Int`) so per-tick steady
--     savings dominate the one-shot enum-replay + thread spawn cost
--     (~15 ms at tick 0 with parallel enabled).
--
-- Session E added per-thread Z3 contexts for primitive components;
-- session S extended to enum-typed components via cross-context
-- datatype replay. Before S the enum vars forced sequential. After S
-- the six graphs solve in parallel.
--
-- BENCHMARK (Apple M4, scripts/bench-demo.sh -s 1, EVIDENT_VALUE_CACHE=0
-- so each tick actually re-solves):
--   Mode                            | wall    | tick0   | wall_post | steady/tick
--   --------------------------------+---------+---------+-----------+------------
--   Default (parallel)              |  53.22ms|  15.43ms|  37.79ms  |  1.20 ms
--   EVIDENT_PARALLEL_SLOW=0         | 100.48ms|   7.72ms|  93.02ms  |  4.46 ms
--
-- → 1.9× faster wall · 2.5× faster wall_post · 3.7× faster per-tick.
--   Tick 0 is more expensive in parallel (~2× — enum replay + thread
--   spawn) but the per-tick savings over 20 ticks dwarf it.

import "stdlib/runtime.ev"

enum Color = Red | Green | Blue

enum DemoState = Searching | Done

fsm coloring(state ∈ DemoState)
    tick ∈ Int = (is_first_tick ? 0 : _tick + 1)
    state_next = (tick ≥ 19 ? Done : Searching)


